text:
Spaghetti and Meatballs ğŸ from Lady and the Tramp ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ³ğŸ•â™¥ï¸

Recipe:
-110g ground beef
-110g ground pork
-30g breadcrumbs
-15g grated Parmesan
-1 egg
-1 cloves garlic, minced
-1 tbsp chopped fresh parsley
-1/2 tsp saltÂ 
-1/2 black pepper
-1/2 tsp dried oregano
-1-2 tbsp milk
-2 tbsp olive oil (for frying)

Sauce:
-1 tbsp olive oil
-1 small onion, finely chopped
-2 cloves garlic, minced
-400g canned crushed tomatoes
-200g canned tomato sauce
-1/2 tsp dried basil
-1/2 tsp dried oregano
-1/2 salt
-1/2 tsp black pepper
-1/2 tsp sugar (optional)
-1/4 cup fresh basil, chopped (optional)

Pasta:
-180g spaghettiÂ 
-salt for boiling water

Instructions:
Mix all meatball ingredients in a bowl. Form 2.5 cm balls. Heat olive oil in a pan and brown meatballs on all sides. Set aside.

In the same pan, sautÃ© onion until soft, then add garlic. Pour in tomatoes and tomato sauce, then season with herbs, salt, pepper, and sugar. Simmer for 20-25 minutes, adding meatballs back in after 5 minutes.

Boil salted water and cook spaghetti until al dente. Drain.

Toss spaghetti with a little sauce. Plate, top with meatballs and more sauce. Garnish with Parmesan and fresh basil.Â

text:
Mushroom Risotto ğŸ„ğŸš from Delicious in Dungeon ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ³ğŸ³

Recipe:
-100g arborio riceÂ 
-3 medium sized mushrooms (e.g., shiitake or oyster), chopped
-60ml white wine
-2-3 cloves garlic, minced
-1 tablespoon unsalted butter
-400-500ml water or stock
-optional: 0.1-0.2g saffron
-1/4 teaspoon salt
-20 grated swiss cheese
-60g grated cheddar cheese
-additional salt to taste

Instructions:
In a pot, bring the water or stock to a simmer and maintain over low heat. In a separate pan, melt the butter over medium heat. Add the minced garlic and sautÃ© until fragrant.Â 

Add the chopped mushrooms to the pan and cook until they release their moisture and become tender. Add the rice to the pan, stirring continuously for about 2 minutes to lightly toast the grains.

Pour in the cooking wine, stirring until it's mostly absorbed by the rice. Dissolve the saffron in the broth or water. Add a ladleful of the warm stock or water to the rice, stirring frequently. Once absorbed, add another ladleful. Continue this process until the rice is al dente and has creamy consistency. This should take about 18â€“20 minutes.Â 

Stir in the Swiss and cheddar cheeses until melted and well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning with additional salt if necessary.Â 

Plate the risotto immediately, garnishing with extra cheese or fresh herbs if desired.

Three Layer Tea Latte ğŸµ from Dr. Stone

Recipe:
-30ml whipped matcha
-30ml milk
-20ml hojicha tea
-2 tbsp gum syrup

To keep the milk separate from the tea, the tea needs to have a higher density than the milk. This requires a significant amount of sugar syrup.

At least 20â€“30% of the total liquid should be sugar syrup.

The thicker (more concentrated) the sugar syrup, the better it will work. Pour the milk very slowly to maintain a clear separation. Cold milk on warm, dense tea enhances the layering effect.

text:
Not long ago, I was invited to a creator event in LA with other food content creatorsâ€”an incredible experience where we all got to cook together. I decided to make one of my favourite desserts, set big expectations for myselfâ€¦ and then completely flopped. FML.

Everything was smooth sailing, but I had doubts about the gelatine available there (probably should have added more but didnâ€™t). Then, when the final mascarpone cream mixture was ready to be whippedâ€”it just wasn't holding structure. Different country, different gelatin strength? Maybe just a poor excuse. You tell me!

While the flavour wasnâ€™t the issue here, I had a golden chance to switch up the plating and save it with a clever touch, but my insecurity kicked in, and I doubled down on the original setup (first pictured), knowing full well in the back of mind that it wouldnâ€™t work. Maybe it was also the pressure of 20 people silently watching, or maybe I just fumbledâ€”either way, itâ€™s something to work on.

I guess, no matter how many times youâ€™ve made something, there are always curveballs. You just have to know how to catch them. More than anything, it reminded me how important it is to adapt in the momentâ€”something Iâ€™ll keep in mind as I move toward opening a business.

RECIPE (1 loaf, 6h prep time):
-350ml roomtemp water
-8g fresh yeast or 3g instant yeast
Mix well.
-500g wheat flour 
-10g salt
Stir until a sticky dough forms.
Cover and let it rest for 3h.
Slightly wet your hands and stretch and fold all 4 edges of the dough. 
Cover and let it rest for 30mins.
Repeat 4x in total.
Preheat the oven to 250C.
Put the dough on a floured working surface and shape into a loaf.
Place in a ovenproof baking dish with parchment paper.
Cover and bake for 30mins.
Remove the lid, lower the temperature to 220C and bake for another 20mins.
Let it cool down completely and enjoy!

RECIPE
Cake batter:
- 2-3 lemons, juice + zest
- 180 g sugar
- 120 g soy milk
- 90 g olive oil (I used extra-virgin)
- 1 tsp vanilla extract
â €
- 250 g all purpose flour
- 1 tsp baking powder
- 1 tsp baking soda
- 1/4 tsp salt
â €
Icing (optional):
- 100 g powdered sugar
- 1 tbsp lemon juice
â €
â¶ Preheat the oven to 180Â°C.
â· Zest the lemons and rub in the sugar to release the flavor and color. Mix with the wet ingredients until well combined.
â¸ In a separate bowl combine the dry ingredients, then add the dry to the wet mix and stir to combine. Donâ€™t overmix the batter.
â¹ Pour the batter into a cake pan lined with parchment paper.
âº Bake at 180Â°C for 45-55 until golden brown.
â» Remove from the oven and allow to cool for 10 minutes in the pan. Then remove the cake from the pan and allow to cool completely.
â¼ If you want, glaze the cake with some icing and let it dry for 1-2 hours. Enjoy!

text:
Vegan Shakshuka ğŸ¤¤ğŸ”¥
â €
Shakshuka is a popular North African and Middle Eastern spiced tomato and pepper sauce that is commonly served with eggs. This is my go-to recipe and itâ€™s one of my favorite things to enjoy my homemade bread with. Of course you can use eggs, but I love to use hummus as an easy & delicious vegan alternative!
â €
RECIPE
- 1-2 tbsp oil
- 1-2 onions
- 1 red pepper
- 4-6 garlic cloves
- 1 tbsp tomato paste
- 2 tsp ground cumin
- 2 tsp paprika
- 1 tsp ground coriander
- 1 tsp cinnamon (optional)
- 400 g good tomatoes (fresh or canned)
- 1-2 tsp harissa paste (or a bit of cayenne/chili)
- salt
- black pepper
- hummus (or eggs) 
- parsley
- crusty bread
â €
â¶ SautÃ© onion with a bit of oil until translucent. Add the peppers and cook for a few minutes, then add the garlic, tomato paste and spices. Cook for 1-2 minutes, then add the tomatoes to the pan.
â· Add as much or little spice as you like, season with salt & pepper. Let it simmer or braise in the oven for 10-30 minutes to intensify the flavors.
â¸ Serve with fresh parsley and some crusty bread. Enjoy!
â €
TIPS
- Whenever I donâ€™t have hummus or want to switch it up, I also like to crumble some tofu into the sauce, resembling the Yemeni â€scrambledâ€œ version of this dish.

text:
Savory Cake  
Everything you need:  
1 small broccoli  
1 large carrot  
Optional: 100 g cooked ham or turkey breast  
4-5 eggs  
100 g feta cheese  
100 g grated Gouda  
Salt and pepper  

Grate the broccoli florets. Then grate the carrot as well. Cut the ham into cubes and add it to the vegetables. Crumble the feta cheese into the mixture and add the eggs. Season with salt and pepper and mix everything well. Spread the mixture on a baking sheet or place it in a baking dish lined with parchment paper, about a thumb's width thick. Sprinkle with Gouda cheese and bake in the preheated oven at 200 degrees Celsius (fan) for about 25 minutes. Baking time may vary depending on the oven. Enjoy!
